1
00:05:59,823 --> 00:06:00,991
I think I can see it.

2
00:06:01,074 --> 00:06:02,200
See what?

3
00:06:02,284 --> 00:06:03,410
The anchor.

4
00:06:03,493 --> 00:06:04,995
There isn't one silly.

5
00:06:05,078 --> 00:06:06,288
There is too.

6
00:06:06,371 --> 00:06:07,998
No, not really.

7
00:06:08,081 --> 00:06:09,291
What is there then?

8
00:06:09,374 --> 00:06:12,252
Well it's just a border
like anywhere else.

9
00:06:12,377 --> 00:06:14,421
She's always seeing
things that aren't there.

10
00:06:14,504 --> 00:06:16,423
Like that mermaid yesterday.

11
00:06:16,506 --> 00:06:18,758
Well Anne will believe
me when she arrives.

12
00:06:18,842 --> 00:06:20,677
Oh she just humors you.

13
00:06:22,304 --> 00:06:23,722
Checkpoint ahead boys.

14
00:06:23,805 --> 00:06:25,682
Now you take it up there and drop anchor.

15
00:06:25,765 --> 00:06:27,517
Milly, come with me and
help me hide my tins

16
00:06:27,601 --> 00:06:29,436
in the backup from the customs, come on.

17
00:06:29,519 --> 00:06:30,353
Okay.

18
00:06:40,155 --> 00:06:41,615
Don't they have tobacco in Hungary?

19
00:06:41,698 --> 00:06:44,951
Yeah of course there are,
but not my favorite kind.

20
00:06:45,035 --> 00:06:46,036
Why Daddy?

21
00:06:47,287 --> 00:06:48,163
Whatever does your mother do with you

22
00:06:48,246 --> 00:06:50,165
when you're at home all day?

23
00:06:50,248 --> 00:06:51,791
Oh she humors me.

24
00:06:52,751 --> 00:06:53,460
Dad.

25
00:06:53,543 --> 00:06:54,294
Hmm?

26
00:06:54,377 --> 00:06:55,128
Customs are arriving.

27
00:06:55,211 --> 00:06:56,046
Oh.

28
00:07:19,611 --> 00:07:21,780
How lovely to see you.

29
00:07:21,863 --> 00:07:24,032
My goodness you get prettier every year.

30
00:07:24,115 --> 00:07:26,493
Come below gentlemen,
I'll show you the papers.

31
00:07:29,496 --> 00:07:30,997
It's wonderful to see you again.

32
00:07:31,081 --> 00:07:32,082
Thank you.

33
00:07:33,792 --> 00:07:35,210
Hello, how are you?

34
00:07:35,293 --> 00:07:36,211
Very well, thank you.

35
00:07:36,294 --> 00:07:38,171
You have got longer since last year.

36
00:07:38,254 --> 00:07:39,005
Maybe.

37
00:07:39,089 --> 00:07:40,215
He's getting fatter.

38
00:07:40,298 --> 00:07:41,216
Hello Michael.

39
00:07:42,550 --> 00:07:43,718
It's good to see you.

40
00:07:46,262 --> 00:07:48,181
Uh-oh I'm going to tell.

41
00:07:48,264 --> 00:07:49,557
Stop it.

42
00:07:49,641 --> 00:07:50,850
Same old Milly.

43
00:07:52,519 --> 00:07:55,021
First, thank you again
for the lovely time

44
00:07:55,105 --> 00:07:57,649
you gave me when I visited
you in London last year.

45
00:07:57,732 --> 00:08:00,360
Oh, that was my pleasure.

46
00:08:00,443 --> 00:08:03,738
And now to see you all
again, it is smushing.

47
00:08:03,822 --> 00:08:04,906
Smushing.

48
00:08:04,990 --> 00:08:06,616
Did you have a good
trip thus far this year?

49
00:08:06,700 --> 00:08:07,617
Oh pretty straightforward.

50
00:08:07,701 --> 00:08:08,618
We came down the Rhine.

51
00:08:08,702 --> 00:08:10,912
Milly said you could
hear The Lorelei singing.

52
00:08:10,996 --> 00:08:12,497
Then through Austria on the Danube.

53
00:08:12,622 --> 00:08:15,291
Well everything seem to
be in order Mr. Stevenson.

54
00:08:15,375 --> 00:08:16,126
Good.

55
00:08:16,209 --> 00:08:17,836
Now, have you anything to declare?

56
00:08:17,919 --> 00:08:21,339
Oh just a little pipe tobacco.

57
00:08:21,464 --> 00:08:22,007
You?

58
00:08:22,090 --> 00:08:22,841
No, nothing.

59
00:08:22,924 --> 00:08:23,675
You?

60
00:08:23,758 --> 00:08:24,509
No, nothing.

61
00:08:24,592 --> 00:08:25,927
There is a man waiting to see you

62
00:08:26,011 --> 00:08:27,303
on the bank Mr. Stevenson.

63
00:08:27,387 --> 00:08:28,513
Oh?

64
00:08:28,596 --> 00:08:30,640
I knew that character was watching us.

65
00:08:30,724 --> 00:08:33,268
You are welcome to go ashore
in our launch if you want.

66
00:08:33,351 --> 00:08:34,978
Oh thank you, I'll just get my coat.

67
00:08:42,068 --> 00:08:45,196
Oh Stevenson, oh my dear fella.

68
00:08:45,280 --> 00:08:47,282
Thank heavens, you're a bit late you know.

69
00:08:47,365 --> 00:08:48,658
I'm Braithwaite from the Legation.

70
00:08:48,742 --> 00:08:49,743
Braithwaite?

71
00:08:49,826 --> 00:08:51,036
Yes, I missed you in Vienna

72
00:08:51,119 --> 00:08:53,455
so we dashed over here with my...

73
00:08:55,373 --> 00:08:58,293
Well the point is, we need
you in Budapest right away.

74
00:08:58,376 --> 00:08:59,461
What?

75
00:08:59,544 --> 00:09:00,962
Yes, Ar-chep's gone sick.

76
00:09:01,046 --> 00:09:02,172
You've got to make the opening speech.

77
00:09:02,255 --> 00:09:03,006
Look I...

78
00:09:03,089 --> 00:09:04,424
Now don't, don't, don't,
don't worry, don't worry.

79
00:09:04,507 --> 00:09:05,592
You can always read his
speech if you get stuck.

80
00:09:05,675 --> 00:09:07,218
But what about my family?

81
00:09:07,302 --> 00:09:09,596
Your fam, oh.

82
00:09:10,847 --> 00:09:12,182
Well that's a bit of a snag isn't it?

83
00:09:12,265 --> 00:09:14,601
Well most certainly,
they've got to come with me.

84
00:09:14,684 --> 00:09:15,602
What in the car?

85
00:09:17,228 --> 00:09:19,272
Well I hate to admit defeat old man, but...

86
00:09:21,816 --> 00:09:23,693
Look Dad, why don't I
take the boat to Budapest

87
00:09:23,777 --> 00:09:24,861
and meet you there?

88
00:09:27,030 --> 00:09:30,742
Well if I must, I suppose I must.

89
00:09:30,825 --> 00:09:31,826
Oh that's my boy.

90
00:09:31,910 --> 00:09:33,661
Now come along, come along now.

91
00:09:33,745 --> 00:09:35,413
Oh but now look here, Milly
will have to come with me.

92
00:09:35,497 --> 00:09:37,207
She's too young to stay here by herself.

93
00:09:37,290 --> 00:09:39,209
No, no, no, I want to go with Anne,

94
00:09:39,292 --> 00:09:41,377
I don't want to go in the rotten old car.

95
00:09:42,295 --> 00:09:43,213
Oh.

96
00:09:43,296 --> 00:09:44,089
Now, stop that Milly.

97
00:09:44,172 --> 00:09:45,381
I'm not gonna have to tell your mother

98
00:09:45,465 --> 00:09:47,133
that you've behaved badly.

99
00:09:47,217 --> 00:09:48,718
Please Mr. Stevenson.

100
00:09:48,802 --> 00:09:51,054
We'll take real good care of her.

101
00:09:51,137 --> 00:09:52,097
Please Daddy.

102
00:09:52,180 --> 00:09:56,142
Oh all right.

103
00:09:56,226 --> 00:09:57,811
All right but now see
that you look after her.

104
00:09:57,894 --> 00:09:59,020
Now come along that's fine old boy.

105
00:09:59,104 --> 00:10:00,605
Now we haven't got a moment
to spare, now come along.

106
00:10:00,688 --> 00:10:01,815
Oh but look here, what about my gear?

107
00:10:01,898 --> 00:10:02,774
I must have a toothbrush.

108
00:10:02,857 --> 00:10:04,192
Oh don't worry, we'll get all that stuff

109
00:10:04,275 --> 00:10:05,902
while you're at the Legation,
now you just hop in there.

110
00:10:05,985 --> 00:10:07,570
Mm-hmm, that's fine now come along.

111
00:10:07,654 --> 00:10:09,072
Come on Dad, in you go.

112
00:10:09,155 --> 00:10:10,240
How do you suggest we do this?

113
00:10:10,323 --> 00:10:13,201
Oh it's very simple, just
forward madame s'il vous plaÃ®t.

114
00:10:13,284 --> 00:10:14,119
Eh, there.

115
00:10:15,078 --> 00:10:16,329
There we are.

116
00:10:16,412 --> 00:10:17,872
OH dear.

117
00:10:18,790 --> 00:10:19,499
Very nice.

118
00:10:19,624 --> 00:10:21,709
Well good-bye.

119
00:10:21,793 --> 00:10:22,627
Bye Dad, see you go.

120
00:10:22,710 --> 00:10:24,087
Bye Dad.

121
00:10:24,170 --> 00:10:25,255
Bye.

122
00:10:28,299 --> 00:10:29,300
Come on, let's go.

123
00:10:34,514 --> 00:10:37,559
Nothing to worry about, just
rely on Savoir Faire.

124
00:10:37,642 --> 00:10:39,978
I don't even know if I brought any.

125
00:10:40,061 --> 00:10:41,896
Fortunately I have enough for two.

126
00:10:44,274 --> 00:10:45,984
As you were.

127
00:10:46,067 --> 00:10:47,277
Passports please.

128
00:10:50,488 --> 00:10:52,699
One American and one English huh.

129
00:10:52,782 --> 00:10:55,785
Well we're not married right.

130
00:10:55,869 --> 00:10:56,953
Have you anything to declare?

131
00:10:57,036 --> 00:10:58,705
I'm glad you asked me that.

132
00:10:58,788 --> 00:11:01,749
I want to declare that three
pair of socks was stolen.

133
00:11:01,833 --> 00:11:03,501
No, no, that was in Austria.

134
00:11:03,585 --> 00:11:04,335
He doesn't want to know that.

135
00:11:04,419 --> 00:11:06,880
He wants to know if you have
any valuable merchandise,

136
00:11:06,963 --> 00:11:09,048
gold, or precious stones?

137
00:11:09,132 --> 00:11:11,217
No, not yet.

138
00:11:11,301 --> 00:11:12,051
Shut up.

139
00:11:12,135 --> 00:11:13,595
And you?

140
00:11:13,678 --> 00:11:16,306
I have only to declare my admiration

141
00:11:16,389 --> 00:11:19,017
for the treasures of your country.

142
00:11:19,100 --> 00:11:21,060
I should like to look in the caravan.

143
00:11:21,144 --> 00:11:21,978
All right.

144
00:11:33,740 --> 00:11:35,033
Open this one please.

145
00:11:45,251 --> 00:11:49,547
Well I thought I'd pick up
a few things in Budapest.

146
00:11:53,468 --> 00:11:54,093
Thank you sir.

147
00:11:56,930 --> 00:12:00,975
Please, I hope you will
enjoy your stay in Hungary.

148
00:12:01,059 --> 00:12:02,143
Thank you.

149
00:12:02,227 --> 00:12:03,937
As you were.

150
00:12:09,567 --> 00:12:11,319
If somebody does not watch them,

151
00:12:11,402 --> 00:12:13,529
they will try to steal the Danube.

152
00:12:13,655 --> 00:12:15,531
I don't think you should have said that.

153
00:12:15,615 --> 00:12:18,284
I'm going to pick up a
few things in Budapest.

154
00:12:18,368 --> 00:12:20,328
Well, maybe I shouldn't have said it.

155
00:12:20,411 --> 00:12:21,246
But I think we should.

156
00:12:21,329 --> 00:12:23,790
I mean we should steal something
just to keep in practice.

157
00:12:23,873 --> 00:12:25,792
A few postage stamps or something.

158
00:12:25,875 --> 00:12:28,628
Why do we always have
to steal an art object?

159
00:12:28,711 --> 00:12:31,631
The trouble with you is that
you always think in pennies.

160
00:12:31,714 --> 00:12:33,383
I think in millions.

161
00:12:35,051 --> 00:12:36,052
You got a cigarette?

162
00:13:00,702 --> 00:13:01,786
Wait a minute.

163
00:13:05,456 --> 00:13:06,874
Michael and I are going to the ship stores

164
00:13:06,958 --> 00:13:08,334
to get some supplies.

165
00:13:08,418 --> 00:13:11,170
You Milly go down to the
market and get some bread.

166
00:13:11,254 --> 00:13:12,380
Get cracking.

167
00:13:12,463 --> 00:13:13,756
You men cracking.

168
00:13:13,840 --> 00:13:14,590
Yes, cracking.

169
00:13:14,674 --> 00:13:15,758
Crocking.

170
00:13:25,310 --> 00:13:26,144
Yes.

171
00:13:27,312 --> 00:13:30,732
Smaller, smaller, for four people.

172
00:13:32,233 --> 00:13:32,984
Four people.

173
00:13:33,067 --> 00:13:33,901
Oh.

174
00:13:35,320 --> 00:13:36,571
No, no, no, no.

175
00:13:41,409 --> 00:13:44,078
Four people, 1/4.

176
00:13:45,621 --> 00:13:47,707
But I can't use all that bread.

177
00:13:48,624 --> 00:13:50,168
Can I help you young lady?

178
00:13:50,251 --> 00:13:51,711
Yes please.

179
00:13:52,712 --> 00:13:55,048
How much bread do you want?

180
00:13:55,131 --> 00:13:57,508
I only want a quarter
of that enormous loaf.

181
00:14:01,888 --> 00:14:03,639
Thank you, that was a great help.

182
00:14:03,723 --> 00:14:05,516
Are you on holiday here?

183
00:14:05,600 --> 00:14:07,435
No, we're going to Budapest in a boat.

184
00:14:07,518 --> 00:14:09,103
My father's going there by car,

185
00:14:09,187 --> 00:14:10,104
to a conference or something.

186
00:14:10,188 --> 00:14:11,939
And what have you come to see?

187
00:14:13,066 --> 00:14:14,817
But I can't think of anything special.

188
00:14:14,901 --> 00:14:16,194
But my brother likes to eat special

189
00:14:16,277 --> 00:14:17,820
because of the ice cream.

190
00:14:17,904 --> 00:14:20,531
Anne says there was some
nice things in the cathedral.

191
00:14:20,615 --> 00:14:22,700
Would you like to see
something really special?

192
00:14:22,784 --> 00:14:24,786
One of the most lovely things in Hungary.

193
00:14:24,869 --> 00:14:27,246
And nobody else will be
able to see it today.

194
00:14:27,330 --> 00:14:28,373
Something secret?

195
00:14:28,456 --> 00:14:29,207
Yeah.

196
00:14:29,290 --> 00:14:30,166
Oh yes, please.

197
00:15:12,250 --> 00:15:14,377
You must be one of the youngest visitors

198
00:15:14,460 --> 00:15:15,962
Saint Laszlo ever had.

199
00:15:17,463 --> 00:15:19,924
They clean it like this every year.

200
00:15:20,007 --> 00:15:21,592
And it's a tradition that the cleaning

201
00:15:21,676 --> 00:15:24,554
shall always be done by the same family.

202
00:15:24,637 --> 00:15:27,640
His grandfather's grandfather
did this before him.

203
00:15:28,516 --> 00:15:33,312
It's solid gold, this is
enamel and precious stones.

204
00:15:33,396 --> 00:15:35,314
It's a great treasure.

205
00:15:35,398 --> 00:15:37,191
It's beautiful.

206
00:15:37,275 --> 00:15:39,444
Now I really have got a secret.

207
00:15:39,569 --> 00:15:41,112
Yes, yes. So.

208
00:15:42,738 --> 00:15:43,656
Thanks for letting me see it.

209
00:17:17,250 --> 00:17:18,960
Quite a gem there isn't it?

210
00:17:19,043 --> 00:17:20,461
I know.

211
00:17:20,545 --> 00:17:21,837
What were you looking at there?

212
00:17:21,921 --> 00:17:23,589
Saint Laszlo of course.

213
00:17:23,673 --> 00:17:25,633
Yes, he must be wonderful.

214
00:17:25,716 --> 00:17:29,303
He is, smashing all
that lovely gold hair

215
00:17:29,387 --> 00:17:31,389
and all those rich jewels.

216
00:17:31,472 --> 00:17:33,224
You seem to know quite
a lot about Saint Laszlo.

217
00:17:33,349 --> 00:17:35,977
He's the most beautiful
thing I've ever seen.

218
00:17:38,020 --> 00:17:39,981
When, how could you have seen him?

219
00:17:40,106 --> 00:17:41,691
It was a very special favor.

220
00:17:41,774 --> 00:17:44,735
I'm the only one who
seem him today actually.

221
00:17:44,819 --> 00:17:48,447
Today, no you must be wrong my dear.

222
00:17:48,531 --> 00:17:49,407
He isn't here today.

223
00:17:49,532 --> 00:17:51,576
I know, they're cleaning it.

224
00:17:51,659 --> 00:17:53,119
The same family do it,

225
00:17:53,202 --> 00:17:55,580
they've been doing it for ever and ever.

226
00:17:55,663 --> 00:17:58,124
You think they'd show
it to me if I ask nicely?

227
00:18:00,459 --> 00:18:01,294
They might.

228
00:18:02,753 --> 00:18:05,131
You're sure you're not imagining all this?

229
00:18:05,214 --> 00:18:07,216
I'll jolly well show
you, the house I mean,

230
00:18:07,300 --> 00:18:09,010
not him 'cause that's a secret.

231
00:18:09,885 --> 00:18:12,597
All right, but I still can't believe it.

232
00:18:12,722 --> 00:18:13,889
Come on, I'll show you.

233
00:18:13,973 --> 00:18:16,392
We have to be very quick,
my brother's waiting for me.

234
00:18:16,475 --> 00:18:17,310
All right.

235
00:18:20,146 --> 00:18:23,149
We must hurry, they'll be
waiting for me at the boat.

236
00:18:23,232 --> 00:18:23,983
A boat.

237
00:18:24,066 --> 00:18:27,320
The White Rabbit, we're
on our way to Budapest.

238
00:18:27,403 --> 00:18:28,446
Oh.

239
00:18:28,529 --> 00:18:30,948
It's there, yellow
house with the green door.

240
00:18:31,032 --> 00:18:31,866
I see.

241
00:18:31,949 --> 00:18:34,118
Good-bye, remember it's a secret.

242
00:18:34,201 --> 00:18:36,078
I will, okay, bye.

243
00:19:07,818 --> 00:19:10,446
The men say they
are very sorry Michael,

244
00:19:10,529 --> 00:19:12,740
but we must return to town.

245
00:19:12,823 --> 00:19:14,492
The chief of police wants to ask us

246
00:19:14,575 --> 00:19:16,702
some questions about something.

247
00:19:16,786 --> 00:19:18,621
He especially wants to talk to Milly.

248
00:19:20,498 --> 00:19:24,794
Me, oh dear I bet it's
about daddy's tobacco tins.

249
00:19:24,877 --> 00:19:25,920
Yes, that could be.

250
00:19:29,548 --> 00:19:30,466
This way please.

251
00:19:37,181 --> 00:19:40,142
Yes, that's the little girl.

252
00:19:41,060 --> 00:19:43,938
I'm afraid something rather
serious has happened.

253
00:19:44,021 --> 00:19:47,233
You remember the golden
head, it's been stolen.

254
00:19:47,316 --> 00:19:50,569
Stolen, it can't be,
who'd do such a thing?

255
00:19:50,695 --> 00:19:51,737
Apart from myself,

256
00:19:51,821 --> 00:19:54,532
you are the only one who saw it yesterday.

257
00:19:54,615 --> 00:19:56,450
How dreadful.

258
00:19:56,534 --> 00:19:59,537
Did you tell anybody
about seeing the head?

259
00:19:59,620 --> 00:20:01,706
I started to tell Harold.

260
00:20:01,789 --> 00:20:03,791
I thought she was making it up as usual.

261
00:20:03,874 --> 00:20:04,875
I knew she had a secret,

262
00:20:04,959 --> 00:20:07,128
but I never dreamed it
was anything like this.

263
00:20:07,253 --> 00:20:10,172
You are the oldest one, no?

264
00:20:10,256 --> 00:20:11,090
Yes sir.

265
00:20:16,178 --> 00:20:18,305
Can you explain this?

266
00:20:18,389 --> 00:20:19,515
That's ours.

267
00:20:19,598 --> 00:20:22,435
The White Rabbit is your boat isn't it?

268
00:20:22,518 --> 00:20:23,519
Yes sir.

269
00:20:23,602 --> 00:20:26,772
This tool was used
to break into the house

270
00:20:26,856 --> 00:20:28,524
and then left behind.

271
00:20:30,151 --> 00:20:31,736
But that's incredible.

272
00:20:31,819 --> 00:20:34,613
Perhaps you took it as a joke.

273
00:20:34,697 --> 00:20:36,866
Certainly not.

274
00:20:36,949 --> 00:20:40,578
Our dad's a detective, we
would never be so stupid.

275
00:20:40,661 --> 00:20:42,663
Fancy anybody leaving direct evidence

276
00:20:42,747 --> 00:20:44,206
on the scene of the crime like that.

277
00:20:44,331 --> 00:20:47,501
It's a put up job, but
how did they get our hammer?

278
00:20:47,585 --> 00:20:50,129
My father's at the police
conference in Budapest,

279
00:20:50,212 --> 00:20:51,505
he'll tell you that we don't normally

280
00:20:51,589 --> 00:20:53,841
go around committing burglaries.

281
00:20:56,177 --> 00:21:01,140
You say that somebody
stole this and then the head?

282
00:21:01,432 --> 00:21:03,100
Well it's the only explanation.

283
00:21:05,811 --> 00:21:08,397
Think hard, you must have told

284
00:21:08,481 --> 00:21:10,608
somebody about the head.

285
00:21:10,691 --> 00:21:12,610
No, I would have remembered.

286
00:21:13,527 --> 00:21:14,278
Uh-oh.

287
00:21:14,361 --> 00:21:15,321
Yes.

288
00:21:15,404 --> 00:21:17,490
There was a man in the
cathedral, he was English.

289
00:21:17,573 --> 00:21:18,949
I showed him the house.

290
00:21:19,033 --> 00:21:20,576
Can you describe him?

291
00:21:23,412 --> 00:21:24,830
Could I be of help?

292
00:21:24,914 --> 00:21:26,123
That's him.

293
00:21:26,248 --> 00:21:28,709
Mr. Palmer, the
London antique dealer aren't you?

294
00:21:28,793 --> 00:21:29,543
Yes,

295
00:21:29,627 --> 00:21:30,836
Allow me to introduce
you to the chief of police.

296
00:21:30,920 --> 00:21:32,046
How do you do?

297
00:21:32,129 --> 00:21:34,256
What a tragedy Father, what a tragedy.

298
00:21:34,340 --> 00:21:36,801
It is him, I showed him the house.

299
00:21:36,884 --> 00:21:39,428
Is this young lady in
some sort of trouble?

300
00:21:39,512 --> 00:21:41,096
It's very embarrassing Mr. Palmer,

301
00:21:41,180 --> 00:21:43,015
but she said she showed you where the head

302
00:21:43,098 --> 00:21:44,600
of Saint Laszlo was
being cleaned yesterday.

303
00:21:45,518 --> 00:21:46,936
What nonsense, I've never seen

304
00:21:47,019 --> 00:21:48,687
this little girl before in my life.

305
00:21:48,771 --> 00:21:50,815
You're telling stories my dear.

306
00:21:50,898 --> 00:21:53,317
It's not true, it's
not true, I did show you.

307
00:21:53,400 --> 00:21:56,153
You must believe me,
really I did show him.

308
00:21:56,278 --> 00:21:58,989
Now this is preposterous,
I insist upon my car

309
00:21:59,073 --> 00:22:01,158
and my hotel room being searched.

310
00:22:01,283 --> 00:22:05,120
Thank you Mr. Palmer,
I'm being forced to ask you

311
00:22:05,204 --> 00:22:07,832
to do that after what the child says.

312
00:22:07,915 --> 00:22:08,749
Naturally.

313
00:22:09,708 --> 00:22:11,377
You know if your mommy
and daddy were here,

314
00:22:11,502 --> 00:22:14,088
I'd have something to say
about your upbringing.

315
00:22:14,171 --> 00:22:17,675
You were at one of those
progressive schools no doubt.

316
00:22:18,592 --> 00:22:19,552
Excuse me sir.

317
00:22:19,635 --> 00:22:21,470
Oh Mr. Palmer.

318
00:22:21,554 --> 00:22:24,974
My father's in Budapest,
but perhaps if you care

319
00:22:25,057 --> 00:22:27,560
to leave me your card, if
an apology is called for

320
00:22:27,643 --> 00:22:28,811
you'll certainly get one.

321
00:22:28,894 --> 00:22:29,979
That's fair enough.

322
00:22:31,689 --> 00:22:32,523
Thank you.

323
00:22:36,151 --> 00:22:37,486
Surely you believe me.

324
00:22:38,529 --> 00:22:40,906
My child, I
don't know what to think.

325
00:22:40,990 --> 00:22:42,825
Except that you must be mistaken.

326
00:22:46,579 --> 00:22:49,498
There, there, it'll be all right.

327
00:23:12,313 --> 00:23:13,564
Have they gone?

328
00:23:13,647 --> 00:23:14,481
Yes.

329
00:23:14,565 --> 00:23:17,026
The police, they're
the same the world over.

330
00:23:17,109 --> 00:23:19,528
Mm-mm, now you may assume

331
00:23:19,612 --> 00:23:21,655
that all police are fools, but I don't.

332
00:23:22,531 --> 00:23:25,284
I think I was right to
take the bull by the horns.

333
00:23:25,367 --> 00:23:26,327
To grab the cup.

334
00:23:26,410 --> 00:23:27,745
No, no, that's just an expression,

335
00:23:27,828 --> 00:23:30,247
meaning that it was wise to
go to the police station,

336
00:23:30,331 --> 00:23:31,498
now you've got that?

337
00:23:31,582 --> 00:23:32,374
Yes.

338
00:23:32,458 --> 00:23:33,709
But what did I say?

339
00:23:33,792 --> 00:23:34,627
When?

340
00:23:36,962 --> 00:23:40,591
Look, do you remember
that job that we did

341
00:23:40,674 --> 00:23:42,259
in Bogno in 1950?

342
00:23:42,343 --> 00:23:43,093
Yes.

343
00:23:43,177 --> 00:23:46,680
Hmm, well we're not
gonna do it that way.

344
00:23:46,764 --> 00:23:47,598
Oh.

345
00:23:48,933 --> 00:23:52,186
Now, what is the obvious thing to do?

346
00:23:53,312 --> 00:23:56,482
Now, what is the obvious thing to do?

347
00:23:56,565 --> 00:23:58,651
I just said that, do you know?

348
00:23:59,902 --> 00:24:01,612
Yeah, the obvious
thing to do is something

349
00:24:01,695 --> 00:24:05,199
that's so obvious that
nobody even suspects that.

350
00:24:05,282 --> 00:24:07,910
So we'll get us a jet plane with the...

351
00:24:07,993 --> 00:24:08,827
No.

352
00:24:10,162 --> 00:24:12,539
A truck, a refrigerator
truck with plenty of ice.

353
00:24:12,623 --> 00:24:13,499
No.

354
00:24:13,582 --> 00:24:14,583
No ice.

355
00:24:14,667 --> 00:24:16,794
No truck, no.

356
00:24:16,877 --> 00:24:18,629
Well, what if we got...

357
00:24:18,712 --> 00:24:20,714
No, no, I'll tell you
what we're gonna do.

358
00:24:20,798 --> 00:24:22,758
We'll make it invisible.

359
00:24:24,510 --> 00:24:25,636
What?

360
00:24:27,554 --> 00:24:28,973
The thing.

361
00:24:29,056 --> 00:24:32,101
What thing?

362
00:24:32,184 --> 00:24:34,061
The object.

363
00:24:34,144 --> 00:24:35,771
What object?

364
00:24:35,854 --> 00:24:37,189
Oh you know what.

365
00:24:37,272 --> 00:24:38,816
No, I don't.

366
00:24:38,899 --> 00:24:39,692
The head.

367
00:24:39,775 --> 00:24:42,027
Oh the golden head, yeah!

368
00:24:44,571 --> 00:24:48,200
Now look, I'll explain it to you

369
00:24:48,283 --> 00:24:49,451
in words of one syllable.

370
00:24:49,535 --> 00:24:52,037
Aww there's no need to be insulting.

371
00:24:52,121 --> 00:24:53,455
Now look, what we're going to do,

372
00:24:53,539 --> 00:24:56,667
yes, we're going to pull
the old double bluff.

373
00:24:58,002 --> 00:24:59,461
The old double bluff.

374
00:24:59,545 --> 00:25:00,379
Yeah.

375
00:25:00,462 --> 00:25:03,841
What is the old double
bluff, what's that?

376
00:25:03,924 --> 00:25:04,925
Well you see those kids on the boat

377
00:25:05,009 --> 00:25:06,510
are in so much trouble already,

378
00:25:06,593 --> 00:25:09,722
all we've got to do is to dig
them in a little bit deeper

379
00:25:09,805 --> 00:25:10,806
then the police will never believe

380
00:25:10,889 --> 00:25:12,224
anything they say at anytime.

381
00:25:13,183 --> 00:25:15,602
That's genius, well
you travel with a genius

382
00:25:15,686 --> 00:25:17,271
who just keeps geniusing.

383
00:25:22,151 --> 00:25:24,486
There's a fly in the coffee.

384
00:25:26,822 --> 00:25:29,658
The main questions
that came to our concern

385
00:25:29,742 --> 00:25:32,411
gentlemen are the following.

386
00:25:32,494 --> 00:25:35,873
Firstly to intensify
the service provided by

387
00:25:35,956 --> 00:25:38,500
the Central International Crime Bureau

388
00:25:38,584 --> 00:25:39,960
so that it will be possible,

389
00:25:40,044 --> 00:25:42,504
not only to furnish any
country requesting it,

390
00:25:42,588 --> 00:25:45,049
with visual data and by radio,

391
00:25:45,132 --> 00:25:49,136
such as photographs and
fingerprints of wanted criminals,

392
00:25:49,219 --> 00:25:50,471
but also to follow this up

393
00:25:50,554 --> 00:25:54,725
with a detailed dossier on microfilm.

394
00:25:54,808 --> 00:25:58,729
Secondly to clarify the
extradition procedure

395
00:25:58,812 --> 00:26:02,733
on criminals who abscond from
one country into another.

396
00:26:03,650 --> 00:26:07,029
We will be pooling information on a

397
00:26:07,112 --> 00:26:08,322
- series of armed robberies.
- Don't bother us now,

398
00:26:08,405 --> 00:26:10,074
he's speaking, yes.

399
00:26:10,157 --> 00:26:12,743
- Similar in outline.
- Oh can't it wait?

400
00:26:12,826 --> 00:26:14,703
Which have effected most of us here at

401
00:26:14,787 --> 00:26:16,413
- one time or another.
- Well if it's that urgent.

402
00:26:16,497 --> 00:26:17,748
And which may well...

403
00:26:17,831 --> 00:26:19,166
Sorry young man, it's urgent.

404
00:26:19,249 --> 00:26:22,127
Oh, okay, yes.

405
00:26:22,211 --> 00:26:25,672
Hello, I think he's on the line.

406
00:26:26,590 --> 00:26:27,925
Hello Daddy, is that you?

407
00:26:28,884 --> 00:26:31,887
Milly, you've chosen rather
an awkward moment darling.

408
00:26:31,970 --> 00:26:36,100
Can I ring you back, I'm making a speech.

409
00:26:36,225 --> 00:26:38,936
But this is really
important, you must listen.

410
00:26:39,019 --> 00:26:40,270
It's about a crook.

411
00:26:40,354 --> 00:26:43,982
He's stolen the golden
head, have you got a pencil?

412
00:26:44,066 --> 00:26:45,651
Oh all right, but give me it quick,

413
00:26:45,734 --> 00:26:47,277
then get off the line will you?

414
00:26:48,821 --> 00:26:52,157
Palmer, P-A-L-M-E-R,

415
00:26:52,241 --> 00:26:55,702
antique dealer, 99-99-Saint James.

416
00:26:55,828 --> 00:26:59,915
Yes, all right now,
will you ring off please?

417
00:27:00,040 --> 00:27:02,167
But how will you let us know?

418
00:27:02,251 --> 00:27:04,211
I'll send you a wire to...

419
00:27:04,294 --> 00:27:05,462
Esztergom.

420
00:27:05,546 --> 00:27:07,589
Esztergom, right goodbye.

421
00:27:09,633 --> 00:27:13,637
My apologies gentlemen, a slight crisis.

422
00:27:14,638 --> 00:27:16,557
And now to return to the more serious

423
00:27:16,640 --> 00:27:19,226
business of catching criminals.

424
00:27:19,309 --> 00:27:21,061
I don't think Daddy was very pleased.

425
00:27:21,145 --> 00:27:23,522
Dad will let us know if
Palmer's a crook or not,

426
00:27:23,605 --> 00:27:25,732
we just have to wait and be patient.

427
00:27:36,618 --> 00:27:39,705
These four paintings are very famous.

428
00:27:39,788 --> 00:27:43,959
They are at least four or 500 years old.

429
00:27:44,042 --> 00:27:46,295
The artist is unknown.

430
00:27:46,378 --> 00:27:50,716
In place of his signature he
only used his initials, M.S.

431
00:28:17,784 --> 00:28:19,494
Shall we move on then?

432
00:28:52,736 --> 00:28:55,447
# If I wasn't shy #

433
00:28:55,530 --> 00:29:00,202
# I would look in your eye #

434
00:29:00,285 --> 00:29:05,290
# And I would find the
way to say the things #

435
00:29:05,499 --> 00:29:08,001
# I'd like to say #

436
00:29:08,085 --> 00:29:11,505
# Some things that I feel #

437
00:29:11,630 --> 00:29:15,759
# I can't never reveal #

438
00:29:15,842 --> 00:29:20,847
# I wish I knew the way to say
the things I'd like to say #

439
00:29:24,226 --> 00:29:29,231
# But how can I ask you to be mine #

440
00:29:31,858 --> 00:29:36,613
# I guess I will have to take my time #

441
00:29:39,366 --> 00:29:43,829
# Sweet words in my heart #

442
00:29:43,912 --> 00:29:47,708
# Tell me, where do I start #

443
00:29:47,791 --> 00:29:52,796
# I only hope perhaps one day #

444
00:29:54,756 --> 00:29:59,761
# I'll say the little
things I'd like to say #

445
00:30:03,640 --> 00:30:05,684
That was very nice Michael, I liked it.

446
00:30:28,040 --> 00:30:31,043
It's him Palmer, with another man.

447
00:30:41,845 --> 00:30:43,263
What are they up to?

448
00:30:43,347 --> 00:30:45,265
It's his accomplice, they
always have an accomplice.

449
00:30:45,349 --> 00:30:47,851
I bet that's why they
didn't mind being searched.

450
00:30:48,935 --> 00:30:50,937
What a stroke of luck them stopping him.

451
00:30:51,021 --> 00:30:52,189
Now we can watch them.

452
00:30:52,272 --> 00:30:54,066
Maybe they've got the
golden head in there.

453
00:30:54,149 --> 00:30:55,567
Gosh, do you really think so?

454
00:30:55,650 --> 00:30:57,194
We could catch 'em red handed.

455
00:30:57,277 --> 00:30:58,612
Then Daddy wouldn't disown us.

456
00:30:58,695 --> 00:31:00,739
He may even get promoted because of this.

457
00:31:08,080 --> 00:31:10,624
Now's our chance, let's tell the others.

458
00:31:10,707 --> 00:31:12,542
No, Michael would never agree.

459
00:31:12,626 --> 00:31:13,835
It's up to us, are you with me?

460
00:31:13,919 --> 00:31:14,878
Of course.

461
00:31:24,596 --> 00:31:25,680
We thought we'd
go for a little stroll.

462
00:31:25,764 --> 00:31:27,641
Don't go to far away.

463
00:31:27,724 --> 00:31:28,725
We won't.

464
00:31:30,352 --> 00:31:31,311
Milly?

465
00:31:31,395 --> 00:31:32,145
Yes?

466
00:31:32,229 --> 00:31:33,647
Don't you go
getting into any more scrapes.

467
00:31:33,730 --> 00:31:35,399
All right.

468
00:32:00,966 --> 00:32:01,925
You want to go inside?

469
00:32:02,008 --> 00:32:02,843
Of course.

470
00:32:42,799 --> 00:32:44,801
It's in there, I saw it.

471
00:32:48,346 --> 00:32:49,181
Come on.

472
00:32:55,270 --> 00:32:56,563
Michael!

473
00:32:56,646 --> 00:32:57,481
What?

474
00:32:58,607 --> 00:33:00,317
It's there in Palmer's caravan.

475
00:33:00,400 --> 00:33:01,610
He's got it, he really has.

476
00:33:01,693 --> 00:33:02,903
Not the golden head.

477
00:33:02,986 --> 00:33:04,488
Yes, Milly saw it in the cabin.

478
00:33:04,571 --> 00:33:06,490
You'd better be right this time.

479
00:33:15,582 --> 00:33:16,666
Good evening.

480
00:33:20,295 --> 00:33:21,254
Oh, come in.

481
00:33:33,016 --> 00:33:33,934
In there.

482
00:33:39,523 --> 00:33:40,899
But I saw it, I know it was there.

483
00:33:40,982 --> 00:33:42,984
They must have moved it.

484
00:33:51,993 --> 00:33:53,203
Oh, there's nothing here.

485
00:34:09,594 --> 00:34:10,971
Now if you're quite satisfied,

486
00:34:11,054 --> 00:34:12,472
perhaps you wouldn't
mind leaving us alone.

487
00:34:12,556 --> 00:34:14,349
My friend here is tired.

488
00:34:19,104 --> 00:34:20,438
Pardon.

489
00:34:20,522 --> 00:34:23,525
But it's true, they're so true.

490
00:34:23,608 --> 00:34:26,778
Young man, I hold you
responsible for this.

491
00:34:26,861 --> 00:34:28,488
You realize that if I wanted to get nasty

492
00:34:28,572 --> 00:34:30,448
I could go to the Legation.

493
00:34:30,532 --> 00:34:33,285
I think that an apology
is called for, don't you?

494
00:34:33,368 --> 00:34:36,621
Yes sir, I apologize sir.

495
00:34:36,705 --> 00:34:38,123
Thank you very much.

496
00:34:39,332 --> 00:34:41,376
Nice kid, that kid.

497
00:34:42,294 --> 00:34:43,420
Get it back out again.

498
00:34:43,503 --> 00:34:44,337
Why.

499
00:34:47,340 --> 00:34:49,342
Well we might as well admit it,

500
00:34:49,426 --> 00:34:51,970
they're not crooks and we
made that whole thing up.

501
00:34:52,971 --> 00:34:56,099
On the contrary I'm
convinced they are crooks.

502
00:34:56,182 --> 00:34:59,060
The man with him looked
about as straight as a pretzel.

503
00:34:59,144 --> 00:35:01,730
Yeah.

504
00:35:01,813 --> 00:35:04,649
You know Dad's book on
how to catch a criminal?

505
00:35:04,733 --> 00:35:05,567
Yes.

506
00:35:05,650 --> 00:35:07,986
Well just add a little
deduction as it says.

507
00:35:08,945 --> 00:35:12,449
Now then, why would they
park right beside us?

508
00:35:12,532 --> 00:35:15,160
Because they wanted to be searched.

509
00:35:15,243 --> 00:35:16,745
Why should they want that?

510
00:35:16,828 --> 00:35:18,121
To make us look foolish.

511
00:35:18,204 --> 00:35:20,624
Now our accusations seem worthless.

512
00:35:20,707 --> 00:35:22,709
Why should they want that?

513
00:35:22,792 --> 00:35:24,336
Because they are guilty.

514
00:35:24,419 --> 00:35:27,297
That's it, you were
right Milly old girl,

515
00:35:27,380 --> 00:35:30,258
and I'm proud of you.

516
00:35:30,342 --> 00:35:31,343
You'd better have a look in Dad's books,

517
00:35:31,426 --> 00:35:32,552
see what else it says.

518
00:35:32,636 --> 00:35:33,345
Yes.

519
00:35:37,057 --> 00:35:38,099
Have you ever heard of anyone

520
00:35:38,183 --> 00:35:40,310
needing a life preserver on the Danube?

521
00:35:40,393 --> 00:35:42,687
I never even heard of the Danube.

522
00:35:43,563 --> 00:35:45,065
You know we've been very successful

523
00:35:45,148 --> 00:35:47,067
in our operation so far.

524
00:35:47,150 --> 00:35:48,652
But with every policeman in the country

525
00:35:48,735 --> 00:35:51,488
looking for what we've got.

526
00:35:51,571 --> 00:35:53,239
What do we got?

527
00:35:54,658 --> 00:35:55,575
The thing.

528
00:35:55,659 --> 00:35:56,451
What thing.

529
00:35:58,328 --> 00:35:59,454
The object.

530
00:35:59,537 --> 00:36:00,413
What object?

531
00:36:01,915 --> 00:36:03,458
The you know what?

532
00:36:03,541 --> 00:36:07,379
Oh the, yeah I know that,
I'm not stupid you know.

533
00:36:07,462 --> 00:36:08,546
Well I think we ought
to put it somewhere

534
00:36:08,630 --> 00:36:11,633
where no one will ever
think of looking for it.

535
00:36:11,716 --> 00:36:13,760
Put it right at the bottom of the river.

536
00:36:13,843 --> 00:36:17,138
Mm-hmm, and then we wouldn't
be able to find it ourselves.

537
00:36:17,222 --> 00:36:18,973
That's right.

538
00:36:19,057 --> 00:36:21,851
